description: From Middle French mors, from Latin morsus (“bite; clasp”), from mordere (“to bite”).

entries.meaning: A clasp or fastening used to fasten a cope in the front, usually decorative. [from 15th c.]

description: Uncertain. Compare Russian морж (morž, “walrus”), Sami morša, Finnish mursu (all attested later).

examples: Then we passed through a great deale of small ice, and sawe, upon some peices, two morses, and upon some, one; and also diuers seales, layeing upon peices of ice.
